<%- include('../../partials/implementer-core.md.ejs', { specificsBlock: `## Rust Specifics

### Error Handling
- Return \`Result<T, E>\` for fallible functions; use the \`?\` operator to propagate errors.
- Define domain errors with \`thiserror\`-derived enums; use \`anyhow\` only at application boundary.
- Never use \`.unwrap()\` or \`.expect()\` outside tests or provably-unreachable paths; comment why.

### Ownership and Lifetimes
- Prefer borrowing (\`&T\`, \`&mut T\`) over cloning; clone only when ownership transfer is necessary.
- Use \`Arc<Mutex<T>>\` for shared mutable state across threads; prefer message-passing channels.
- Annotate lifetimes explicitly when the compiler cannot infer them — never use \`'_\` to silence errors.

### Testing
- Use \`#[cfg(test)] mod tests { ... }\` for unit tests colocated in the same file.
- Use \`cargo test\` for all test runs; integration tests live in \`tests/\`.
- Use \`proptest\` or \`quickcheck\` for property-based testing of pure functions.

### Anti-patterns to avoid
- Never use \`unsafe\` without a \`// SAFETY:\` comment explaining the invariant.
- Never use \`Box<dyn Error>\` as a return type in library code — define a concrete error type.
- Never hold a \`MutexGuard\` across an \`.await\` point.
- Never use \`std::mem::forget\` to prevent destructors — use \`ManuallyDrop\` with justification.
- Never ignore \`#[must_use]\` results — handle or explicitly discard with \`let _ = ...\`.` }) %>
